    <div class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="faq-item">
<button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">1. What are the 4 Purusharthas?<span class="faq-icon">+</span></button>
<div class="faq-a" style="display:none;"><p>The four Purusharthas are: Dharma (righteous conduct and duty), Artha (wealth, prosperity, and practical achievement), Kama (desire, pleasure, and the enjoyment of beauty), and Moksha (liberation from the cycle of birth and death). Together they form the complete framework for a meaningful, fulfilled, and spiritually progressive human life.</p></div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">2. Which Purushartha is most important?<span class="faq-icon">+</span></button>
<div class="faq-a" style="display:none;"><p>All four are important, but they are arranged in a hierarchy. Dharma is the foundation and governs all others — Artha and Kama must be pursued within its boundaries. Moksha is the ultimate aim that transcends and fulfils the other three. The Mahabharata says that without Dharma, Artha becomes greed and Kama becomes addiction.</p></div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">3. What is the difference between Artha and Kama?<span class="faq-icon">+</span></button>
<div class="faq-a" style="display:none;"><p>Artha refers to material means and prosperity — wealth, property, power, and the practical resources needed to sustain life. Kama refers to desire, pleasure, and the enjoyment of beauty — including love, sensory pleasure, artistic expression, and all forms of human delight. Artha provides the means; Kama describes the enjoyment.</p></div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">4. Does Hinduism allow the pursuit of wealth?<span class="faq-icon">+</span></button>
<div class="faq-a" style="display:none;"><p>Absolutely. The Rigveda invokes Lakshmi (goddess of prosperity) as a divine blessing. The Arthashastra dedicates an entire science to the ethical pursuit of wealth. The householder stage of life (Grihastha Ashrama) explicitly requires material prosperity to fulfil family and social duties. Wealth is honoured when acquired through righteous means (Dharmic Artha).</p></div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">5. What is Moksha and why is it the highest Purushartha?<span class="faq-icon">+</span></button>
<div class="faq-a" style="display:none;"><p>Moksha is liberation from the cycle of birth, death, and rebirth — the realisation of the soul's eternal, blissful nature as Brahman. It is the highest Purushartha because while the other three aims provide temporary satisfaction, Moksha provides permanent, unconditional freedom and bliss. The Katha Upanishad calls it Shreyas — the ultimately auspicious — as opposed to Preyas, the immediately pleasant.</p></div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">6. How do the Four Ashramas relate to the Purusharthas?<span class="faq-icon">+</span></button>
<div class="faq-a" style="display:none;"><p>The Four Ashramas (stages of life) provide a temporal framework for pursuing the Purusharthas in the right proportion at the right time. Student life focuses on Dharma. Householder life engages all four. Retirement gradually releases Artha and Kama. Renunciation focuses entirely on Moksha. The wisdom is in the progression — not denial of any aim, but the gradual evolution toward freedom.</p></div>
</div>

